late the nerve clusters through the skin in the same way as stopping blood flow. While I was reading about the sensation, I saw somewhere that it could be triggered with an excessive amount of vibration like in the case of motorcycle riders while they grip their bikes over jumps, which is known as, &quot;cyclist&#39;s hands&quot;. This is why I&#39;m thinking a directed sound device could create the vibrations with a high enough frequency."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1441566940,"creation_date":1395804621,"body":"<p>Underneath the superficial layers of your skin there are receptors which sense pressure, temperature and pain. These receptors are part of the peripheral nervous system which senses stimuli and they take the message conveying details about the stimulus to the somatosensory cortex of the brain. Here is where the perception of pain, burning, pressure etc is ultimately made. To take the simplest example, if you stop blood flow for a short amount of time in a limb, these receptors are activated, and will send signals to the brain that are interpreted as tingling or numbness. With more severe pain, different receptors are activated which , again, project to the same brain area but a different message is read out. If the pressure from one limb is removed, the receptors will go back to normal function as blood flow is restored.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nociceptor\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nociceptor<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.scholarpedia.org/article/Mammalian_mechanoreception\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.scholarpedia.org/article/Mammalian_mechanoreception<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":16082,"question_id":16032,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1441566940}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/16032/what-causes-paresthesia-pins-and-needles-at-a-cellular-level","last_activity_date":1441566940,"creation_date":1395645235,"answer_count":1,"title":"What causes Paresthesia (Pins and Needles) at a cellular level?","body":"<p>I've looked it up in plenty of places like the Wikipedia page and such, and it is clear that the most common cause of Paresthesia is either a fair amount of pressure on a specific patch of skin causing lack of blood flow to the specific nerve endings in that limb (not to be confused with a stop in blood flow to the limb altogether) or a much stronger amount of pressure on that patch of skin for a shorter amount of time. This, although the most common cause, is not nearly the only one, which could be anywhere from simply sleeping on the wrong side of the bed to a lethal injection. I'm wondering what happens to the nerve cells that are affected at a cellular level, and what causes it at a cellular level. The level at which pounds per square inch aren't what is being noticed.<\/p>\n","question_id":16032,"tags":["human-biology","neuroscience","cell-biology","sleep","blood-circulation"],"score":7,"accepted_answer_id":16082,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":473,"up_vote_count":7},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/61088ee58466316218f96ae12fb35c9a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13388,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13388/xelo747","reputation":463,"display_name":"xelo747"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f59f7acf0f314aa32ca7c03950e9e6f5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":587,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/587/chelonian","reputation":253,"display_name":"Chelonian"},"score":0,"post_id":36646,"edited":false,"creation_date":1441554946,"comment_id":64166,"body":"I edited this to clean up some of the misuses of terminology. One quick suggestion: the names of these ions are not capitalized (&quot;Potassium&quot;, etc.). In fact, more often you will just see K+, Ca++, Na+, and Cl-, which is more convenient to write. Also, there is no such thing as the resting potential for an ion, just for the whole neuron; for the ion, it is the equilibrium potential or reversal potential. Etc."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f59f7acf0f314aa32ca7c03950e9e6f5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":587,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/587/chelonian","reputation":253,"display_name":"Chelonian"},"score":0,"post_id":36646,"edited":false,"creation_date":1441555034,"comment_id":64168,"body":"&quot;This makes me think that this is not a phenomena explained by a neuron at rest.&quot; Why not? If the neuron is not spiking--which it is not in your example--it is at rest."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/61088ee58466316218f96ae12fb35c9a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13388,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13388/xelo747","reputation":463,"display_name":"xelo747"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1438908708,"creation_date":1438811951,"body":"<p><a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2FBF01868866\" rel=\"nofollow\">This paper<\/a> and <a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/neu.480090107/abstract;jsessionid=5CDE9C159B1B689F043D9C3EC4DC8C8B.f04t03?systemMessage=Wiley%20Online%20Library%20will%20have%20intermittent%20access%20on%208th%20August%202015%20from%2010%3A00-16%3A00%20BST%20%2F%2005%3A00-11%3A00%20EDT%20%2F%2017%3A00-23%3A00%20SGT%20for%20essential%20maintenance.%20%20Apologies%20for%20the%20inconvenience.\" rel=\"nofollow\">this paper<\/a> supports the second possibility I hypothesized. <strong>That is a increase in external Calcium concentration leads to an increase in conductance of Potassium.<\/strong> <\/p>\n\n<p>While the increasing the external Potassium concentration can be shown to depolarize the cell with by calculating the Nernst potential for the Ion, the Calcium Ion has a non-intuitive effect. This means if one increases the outside concentration of Calcium Ions then inevitably there will be a small increase in the internal concentration of Calcium ions on the inside. This will slightly bias the Calcium Activated Potassium Ions to be a little more open. Thus raising the conductance of Potassium. This will mean there is a net hyperpolarizing current keeping the cell less excitable. <\/p>\n","answer_id":36654,"question_id":36646,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1438908708}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/36646/doubling-the-concentration-of-extracellular-calcium-hyperpolarizes-a-neuron-why","last_activity_date":1441556301,"creation_date":1438795606,"answer_count":1,"title":"Doubling the concentration of extracellular calcium hyperpolarizes a neuron. Why?","body":"<p>I was doing some back of the envelope calculations to try to answer <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/11026/how-does-extracellular-potassium-ion-concentration-and-calcium-ion-concentration\">this<\/a> question in more mathematical terms. Essentially the question states: Why does increasing the extracellular potassium concentration depolarize a neuron, while increasing the extracellular calcium concentration hyperpolarize the neuron?  <\/p>\n\n<p>My initial thought was that there is a change in the equilibrium potential for each ion. Working this out however I realized I was wrong in my reasoning; my math proved me wrong.<\/p>\n\n<p>Doubling the concentration of extracellular potassium makes the equilibrium potential of potassium 17.8 mV more positive. For calcium, it increases the driving force by 8.9 mV (based on room 300 K temperature). What this means to me is that both will cause the resting potential of the neuron to become slightly more positive, though calcium less so. <\/p>\n\n<p>This is indeed obvious: adding more positive ions to the outside of the cell increases the driving force for that ion, and assuming there is any conductance (albeit small) then there will be some depolarization of the neuron. <\/p>\n\n<p>This makes me think that this is not a phenomena explained by a neuron at rest. Some other mechanism is responsible for increased extracellular calcium causing the neuron to hyperpolarize.<\/p>\n\n<p>My possible guesses:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p>If the calcium concentration is doubled, then the driving force for calcium increases, so there is more influx of calcium and thus the internal calcium concentration will increase. Because the concentration of calcium ions on the inside was previously near zero, now that internal concentration will rise to be some significant number, thereby hyperpolarizing the neuron.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>The internal concentration of calcium rises slightly, but instead of (or perhaps in conjunction with) lowering the resting potential directly, there is more activation of <strong>calcium-activated potassium channels<\/strong>, thus raising the conductance of potassium ions, and thus ultimately hyperpolarizing the neuron.<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>Am I on the right track or am I missing something? <\/p>\n","question_id":36646,"tags":["neurophysiology","electrophysiology"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":212,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1441556301},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-ZuUOhLYURMQ/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAKQ/xzC1mFOkj9c/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":14855,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14855/punarbasu-roy","reputation":158,"display_name":"Punarbasu Roy","accept_rate":25},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b10de963b115fd0720d6a558fd1ac06c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10456,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10456/march-ho","reputation":5867,"display_name":"March Ho","accept_rate":80},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/nOk2h.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15136,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15136/wolgast","reputation":522,"display_name":"Wolgast","accept_rate":86},"score":1,"post_id":31639,"edited":false,"creation_date":1429789095,"comment_id":53134,"body":"Note that X-inactivation is a random process. Therefore not all indivduals will have 50% cells lacking the healthy allele (as you write). This is a process known as skewing. One heterozygotic could have no cells with the faulty allele, all cells with the faulty, or any other intermediate form (this follows a Gaussian distribution in the population). Thus heterozygotes display asymptomatic - mild - severe phenotypes."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b10de963b115fd0720d6a558fd1ac06c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10456,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10456/march-ho","reputation":5867,"display_name":"March Ho","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":31639,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/nOk2h.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15136,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15136/wolgast","reputation":522,"display_name":"Wolgast","accept_rate":86},"edited":false,"creation_date":1429789620,"comment_id":53136,"body":"@Wolgast While this is true and the percentage of cells with inactivation of the faulty allele does in fact follow a Gaussian distribution, the law of large numbers makes it extremely unlikely that the deviation from 50% would be very large. Answer was updated to account for these factors."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":1,"post_id":31639,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/nOk2h.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15136,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15136/wolgast","reputation":522,"display_name":"Wolgast","accept_rate":86},"edited":false,"creation_date":1441554695,"comment_id":64165,"body":"@Wolgast. Also not all genes on Barr bodies are inactivated. There are some regions where you will see a small amount of expression. As March Ho pointed out, hemophilia appears to be a dosage dependent disease and as long as enough Megakaryocytes are expressing the functional allele, then the disease will be masked in heterozygous females."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1429789813,"creation_date":1429784949,"body":"<p>X-linked Hemophilia <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haemophilia#Genetics\" rel=\"nofollow\">is caused by<\/a> the lack of production of the clotting factors VIII or IX. It is not inherited dominantly, but instead inherited in an X-linked recessive manner.<\/p>\n\n<p>These proteins are produced in multiple regions around the body. In a female heterozygous for the gene coding for Factor VIII or IX, X-inactivation would randomly prevent one of the chromosomes from expressing its allele. Therefore, the production of active Factor VIII or IX would only occur in half the cells which have the faulty allele inactivated. <\/p>\n\n<p>However, half the production of the relevant factor results in a close to normal phenotype, as the hemophilic phenotype would not manifest unless the clotting factor activity levels are very low. <\/p>\n\n<p>This <a href=\"http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/779322-overview\" rel=\"nofollow\">Medscape article on hemophilia<\/a> states that:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Normal values for FVIII assays are 50-150%. Values in hemophilia are as follows:<\/p>\n  \n  <p>Mild: >5%<\/p>\n  \n  <p>Moderate: 1-5%<\/p>\n  \n  <p>Severe: &lt; 1%<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Therefore, despite X-inactivation reducing the production of clotting factors by 50%, the heterozygous female still displays the healthy, non-hemophilic phenotype.<\/p>\n\n<p>While the clotting factor concentration can only be reduced to approximately 50% of normal, it is still possible for heterozygotes to suffer from mild hemophilia. This is because <a href=\"http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/779322-overview#aw2aab6b2b2\" rel=\"nofollow\">other genetic factors<\/a> may also affect the hemophilia phenotype. <\/p>\n\n<p>For example, the gene encoding FVIII may have point mutations which reduce the effectiveness of the protease, therefore reducing activity levels below the expected 50%. Mutations in regulatory elements or interacting proteins may also result in hemophilia due to the regulatory elements downregulating the expression or activity of the protein. <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Approximately 40% of cases of severe FVIII deficiency arise from a large inversion that disrupts the FVIII gene. Deletions, insertions, and point mutations account for the remaining 50-60% of the F8C defects that cause hemophilia A.<\/p>\n  \n  <p>Low FVIII levels may arise from defects outside the FVIII gene, as in type IIN von Willebrand disease, in which the molecular defect resides in the FVIII-binding domain of von Willebrand factor. <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","answer_id":31639,"question_id":31635,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1429789813}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/31635/in-human-females-one-x-chromosome-is-inactivated-forming-barr-body-then-how-exa","last_activity_date":1441551683,"creation_date":1429781206,"answer_count":1,"title":"In human females one X chromosome is inactivated forming Barr Body. Then How exactly Haemophilia is dominant? check description for details","body":"<p>Suppose a female has one X chromosome normal and one chromosome with Haemophilic gene. Now suppose if the X chromosome which is normal is inactivated will the female show haemophilia?<\/p>\n","question_id":31635,"tags":["genetics"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":31639,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":153,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1429781332},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/689e875aaece01eefa065cd98817a533?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":15109,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15109/charles","reputation":270,"display_name":"Charles","accept_rate":29},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0d7c5cbd0c2f965a3712ff687c53f997?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14552,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14552/aaaaaa","reputation":2058,"display_name":"aaaaaa"},"score":0,"post_id":38559,"edited":false,"creation_date":1441515621,"comment_id":64141,"body":"can you clarify language? Is it that outcrossing is mating between different populations, whereas crossbreeding is mating between members of inbred populations? E.g. mating between european and asian peasants <i>versus<\/i> mating between members of european and asian royal families."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0d7c5cbd0c2f965a3712ff687c53f997?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14552,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14552/aaaaaa","reputation":2058,"display_name":"aaaaaa"},"score":0,"post_id":38559,"edited":false,"creation_date":1441515711,"comment_id":64142,"body":"<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crossbreed\" rel=\"nofollow\">this article<\/a> mentions both outcrossing and crossbreeding. Language seems confusing to me"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id":38559,"edited":false,"creation_date":1441518162,"comment_id":64144,"body":"I don&#39;t think there is any accepted clear definitions of outbreeding vs crossbreeding. Therefore, definitions should be provided in the post."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0d7c5cbd0c2f965a3712ff687c53f997?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14552,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14552/aaaaaa","reputation":2058,"display_name":"aaaaaa"},"score":0,"post_id":38559,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"edited":false,"creation_date":1441524310,"comment_id":64148,"body":"@Remi.b my point exactly. Although, broadly, if you cross inbre(a)d species, you get less variation than crossing more wild-typish (forgive me) animals"}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/38559/overcoming-inbreeding-depression","last_activity_date":1441520699,"creation_date":1441505826,"answer_count":0,"title":"Overcoming Inbreeding Depression","body":"<p>When inbreeding depression occurs, a genetically unrelated individual is mated with the animal to introduce genetic variability and remove homozygosity. In this case either outbreeding or crossbreeding may be carried out. Is there any preference for either technique over the other? \nOut-breeding here refers to mating between two individuals in the same breed, but no recent common ancestors. \nCross-breeding refers to mating between two individuals of different breeds entirely. <\/p>\n","question_id":38559,"tags":["genetics","animal-husbandry"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":78,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1441520699},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/42dbbf5840ed345d3d62ad982b350358?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17255,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17255/jchwebdev","reputation":131,"display_name":"jchwebdev"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f47c5bf8326ea60124bb9d8e2facd99c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3394,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3394/biozic","reputation":508,"display_name":"biozic"},"score":1,"post_id":36783,"edited":false,"creation_date":1439363281,"comment_id":61513,"body":"Lice, for example, live on the (hair of the) head, which seems specific. Some other insects bite where the skin is accessible, and that can just depends on our clothing habits."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/wOmeM.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16982,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16982/biologydave","reputation":21,"display_name":"biologydave"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1441492127,"creation_date":1441396581,"body":"<p>There are at least two sources that influence patterns of behavior: the individual that is doing the biting, and the individual that is being bitten.<\/p>\n\n<p>The example of lice in one of the comments is a good example.  Three categories of lice that get on humans are: head lice, body lice, and pubic lice.  They are related species (possibly the same species in some cases - <a href=\"https://www.insidescience.org/content/are-head-and-body-lice-same-species/550\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.insidescience.org/content/are-head-and-body-lice-same-species/550<\/a>), but each type has their own preference for habitat and feeding.  There are all kinds of reasons for a species to have a preference, and some stick to those preferences quite strongly.<\/p>\n\n<p>As for your mosquitoes, their absolute preferences are still not known but blood seeking insects do have their senses attuned to clues such as carbon dioxide and heat (that help identify potential hosts) as well smells and other influences on their senses.  There might be something special about the side of your right knee as far as mosquito senses go, but not every individual in a species sees, smells, hears, etc. the same way.  My brother has a gene that makes broccoli taste very bitter, but I am fortunate to not have those taste buds.  Color blindness is another example of differences in perception, but even without being color blind, what you see as red is probably not how someone else sees red due to natural variations in the patterns of sensory cells in the eye.  For a consistent pattern of behavior from the mosquitoes, in spite of individual differences we still need to consider another source of variation that might lead to this mosquito preference: the host.<\/p>\n\n<p>If the variation of individual mosquitoes is trumped by a consistent pattern of predation, perhaps the mediating factor is the host.  Your knee could have a special smell, or other sensory flag that attracts mosquitoes.  There are efforts to understand how a mosquito's perception directs who gets bitten: <a href=\"http://www.scientificamerican.com/video/future-repellents-mess-with-mosquit2013-12-23/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.scientificamerican.com/video/future-repellents-mess-with-mosquit2013-12-23/<\/a> .  Not enough is known yet about the preferences of mosquitoes to say for sure what makes your knee so good.  There is also a chance that your knee is not special to the mosquito because it appears the most appetizing.  <\/p>\n\n<p>Host behavior is another possible influence.  The knee is just far enough away from the reach of your hands.  Conscious or absentminded grooming would both be limited at that distance.  The knee may also be better than an ankle or a foot, because of what is worn or because the knee moves less than the lower leg during walking and other movements.  If you are bitten on the lateral (outside) side of your knee, this would add evidence to this hypothesis of your movement influencing mosquito behavior, because the inside of your knee more frequently brushes against the other leg.  The frequency of the inside of the knee being a safe place for a meal is much lower.<\/p>\n\n<p>As for why it's the right knee rather than the left, there is  possibility that that is also a reflection of you, rather than the pests.  Humans display preferences in dominance for both hands and feet.  One side of your body may be selected more often than another because of you being right- or left-handed, or right- or left-footed.  This could affect grooming habits (how you swat at the bugs), how your cross your legs, which side you carry items or lean against other objects which might brush against the body, influence how well you spray yourself with bug repellent or who knows what else.  (Just for curiosity's sake, ¿are you right-handed or are you left-handed?)<\/p>\n\n<p>In short: There's a lot of evidence to collect before we could come to a definitive answer.  There are a lot of possibilities, including that your knee may not be the tastiest spot, but rather a relatively safe spot for dinner.<\/p>\n\n<p>For more unempirical thoughts on the relationship of insects to the lower limbs, please see: <a href=\"http://fishboyridesagain.blogspot.com/2005/11/bugs-and-trousers.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://fishboyridesagain.blogspot.com/2005/11/bugs-and-trousers.html<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":38522,"question_id":36783,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1441492127}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/36783/can-biting-insects-detect-specific-places-on-a-host-body","last_activity_date":1441492127,"creation_date":1439360078,"answer_count":1,"title":"Can Biting Insects Detect Specific Places On A Host Body?","body":"<p>I'm gonna make a presumptive statement: It -seems- as though I get bitten by mosquitos and other biting insects in -exactly- the same places over and over. I mean within a few mm. Is that true?<\/p>\n\n<p>If true, that implies that insects have a mechanism to detect certain preferred spots in order to get blood or whatever they want. (Location of blood vessels? Sweat glands?)<\/p>\n\n<p>And if that is so, what -is- that mechanism? What are they going for? And how does this detection work?<\/p>\n\n<p>IOW: How do they know to bite me exactly on the side of my right knee over and over and over... but never on other spots?<\/p>\n","question_id":36783,"tags":["entomology","parasitology"],"score":6,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":56,"up_vote_count":6},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/332385e9d9b2df9e42f714c89f9b966e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17472,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17472/sagita-biondo","reputation":18,"display_name":"Sagita Biondo"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/eIiWG.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":8059,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8059/macedon93","reputation":124,"display_name":"Macedon93","accept_rate":67},"score":1,"post_id":37326,"edited":false,"creation_date":1440902899,"comment_id":62683,"body":"Is this a serious question.. ?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b10de963b115fd0720d6a558fd1ac06c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10456,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10456/march-ho","reputation":5867,"display_name":"March Ho","accept_rate":80},"score":3,"post_id":37326,"edited":false,"creation_date":1440911476,"comment_id":62694,"body":"I must add that it is <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/women/news/20020802/dont-suck-snakebite\" rel=\"nofollow\"><b>not<\/b> possible to save someone by sucking venom from a bite<\/a>."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":1,"post_id":37326,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/eIiWG.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":8059,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8059/macedon93","reputation":124,"display_name":"Macedon93","accept_rate":67},"edited":false,"creation_date":1440915611,"comment_id":62700,"b