28,"body":"The book in question is more of an informational pamphlet than a scholarly monograph. The sort of thing that you might find someone handing out on a street corner. The sophistication of composition is at about the second year UG level. The problem I have with this post is that the term &quot;Genetic Entropy&quot; has no clear sense, and may mean different things to different people. The notion seems to approximate: &quot;The Shannon-entropy of the human genomic sequence&quot;. Shannon-entropy measures information content in bits, in contrast to thermodynamic entropy which uses energy units to measure disorder."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2cea341f9bd407af114ff83462b0db98?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15100,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15100/lucian09474","reputation":137,"display_name":"Lucian09474"},"score":0,"post_id":36731,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"edited":false,"creation_date":1439244138,"comment_id":61440,"body":"@Remi.b should I delete this question?, I thought it was silly to ask the question we are having discussion about this and I had no way of defending natural selection, as like I stated I am only familiar with genomic research. In the book a lot of analogies are used to make the reader understand. the author is a 25+ year Cornell University professor, so he is not just some guy. The argument he poses is used very commonly from creationist I come around ( I am heavily surrounded by creationist views) and really it is an eye opener to me how passionate creationist are about &quot;debunking evolution&quot;"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexch