e our insulin gene into a fully functional protein that works to control our blood sugar, just as if it had been produced in our own pancreas. And what is gestational development if not the evolutionary program executed over a very short period of time?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":37479,"edited":false,"creation_date":1441252841,"comment_id":62989,"body":"If we start from the fusion of two gametes, then at early stages of development that amazing eye is just a collection of light sensitive cells without an iris, cornea, lens, etc. basically is the proto-eye that our evolutionary ancestors survived with. As genes changed and better vision provided selective advantage, then those steps were preserved through evolution until we get to the eye we have today, which isn&#39;t so great when you compare it to that of raptors, or nocturnal animals, or animals that can see in a wider spectrum than we can."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":37479,"edited":false,"creation_date":1441253215,"comment_id":62990,"body":"We even start out with a notochord at the early stages of development, which as the evolutionary program is carried out during gestational development becomes the discs between the vertebrae. As our common ancestors evolved beyond simple vertebrates, they developed small incremental changes that eventually extended the CNS into a spinal cord."}],"down_vote_count":3,"last_activity_date":1441238309,"creation_date":1441238309,"body":"<p>It can't be explained by evolution, at least not very well.  There is zero evolutionary advantage for an organism to have half of the characteristics needed for vision, in fact, multiple half formed mechanisms would be a huge detriment.  That said, consider the hundreds of the complex systems present within humans? Adding time to the equation does not solve this fundamental paradox.  If one of those mechanisms in a complex system does not work, the system does not work, if one of the systems in a human body does not work, it is like the person does not live (consider that of the hundreds of systems within a human body, most are essential to sustaining life).  As a medical doctor I can attest to how unbelievably complex the human body is.  I am not saying there is a god, but I also can't believe that time and mutation were enough to provide for the complexity we see in humans and other organisms.  <\/p>\n","answer_id":37479,"question_id":2958,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2958/how-does-evolution-produce-complex-organs","last_activity_date":1441238309,"creation_date":1342820689,"answer_count":2,"title":"How does evolution produce complex organs","body":"<p>I've been wondering lately how evolution manages to produce complex organs. It is pretty obvious to me how evolution would select some minor traits like size, resistnce to illness or climate. There is a mutation where some organisms are slightly different and better traits are selected. However I cannot imagine how an organism will mutate to have lets say lungs at once and unless organism has a functional organ there is no reason for the trait to be selected. So how does evolution produce complx organs?<\/p>\n","question_id":2958,"tags":["evolution"],"score":15,"accepted_answer_id":2962,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":2068,"up_vote_count":15},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c22e05beb9dca5aa56f13b1bd7831bb3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":15503,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15503/mijail","reputation":66,"display_name":"Mi