s during development<\/a>. <\/p>\n\n<p>In the case of eggs laid underground, as in sea turtle eggs, the leathery shell is still permeable to oxygen. The sand restricts oxygen flow, but turtles <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/918411\" rel=\"nofollow\">seem to take care to not bury their eggs too deep for oxygen to diffuse to their developing nest<\/a>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":37449,"question_id":37422,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/37422/how-does-the-embryo-inside-a-shelled-egg-get-oxygen","last_activity_date":1441185832,"creation_date":1441114547,"answer_count":1,"title":"How does the embryo inside a shelled egg get oxygen?","body":"<p>If I'm not mistaken a typical animal in the womb will get oxygen via the umbilical cord from the mother. Thus allowing it to \"breathe\" in a liquid environment. I thought maybe shells are permeable and allow air to come in through the shell, but then I thought of eggs laid in the ground like turtles do.<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>How do animals in soft/hard shells get their oxygen?<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","question_id":37422,"tags":["breathing","eggs"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":37449,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":98,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1441171184},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/63e4f7c36cfb54861bc2c2518bdb7cf2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":8986,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8986/trejder","reputation":132,"display_name":"trejder"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb3c0063d438705f86396a8abc1b04a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12877,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12877/cmosychuk","reputation":4410,"display_name":"CMosychuk"},"score":3,"post_id":37428,"edited":false,"creation_date":1441141690,"comment_id":62892,"body":"A weevil perhaps? Somewhere to start!"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i