ise is flow cytometry scores for the offspring of \"triploid\" intermediates would distribute differently if the issue was length versus count. Fine distribution would indicate \"aneuploids\" because of counts whereas wide distribution would indicate length because length differences are concentrated in only a few chromosomes. <\/p>\n\n<p>This basic premise proved faulty since flow cytometry scores indicate fine distribution (genome size scores reflecting every potential aneuploid between triploid and tetraploid) but documented chromosome counts indicate the issue is length.<\/p>\n\n<p>What are the normal distribution patterns in terms of genome size for multigenerational offspring between 2 species having wide differences in chromosome length?<\/p>\n\n<p>.<\/p>\n","question_id":37188,"tags":["polyploidy","flow-cytometry"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":95,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1441133642},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/uYz1G.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17629,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17629/luke-james-emery","reputation":101,"display_name":"Luke James Emery"},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/37432/is-it-better-to-eat-something-that-is-more-or-less-related-to-humans","last_activity_date":1441129914,"creation_date":1441127925,"answer_count":0,"title":"Is it better to eat something that is more or less related to humans?","body":"<p>My question is, would it be better to eat something like a sea cucumber or would be it better to eat a chimpanzee?  Maybe this isn't a dichotic answer.  Is it better to eat something in between, like a chicken?  I'm thinking a chicken has more nutrients inline with what humans need compared to a sea cucumber, but also that it is different enough to reduce the risk of zoonotic diseases that afflict chimps and humans, for example.<\/p>\n","question_id":37432,"tags":["human-biology","food","nutrition"],"score":0,"down