:1441059553,"creation_date":1441059553,"body":"<p>Nice answer from WYS. I would have been inclined to say that the ribosome translates one polypeptide and any associations happen post translation. Insulin is interesting in that one polypeptide is produced and then cleaved to form components of the protein so that one could say multiple parts are made at the same time if I understand this correctly. Generally the complexities of a protein are introduced after the ribosome has done its job of translation to form one string of amino acids. Protein interactions are a matter of great interest now. I'm not sure one can say any protein is formed independently but is more part of a large ochestra.<\/p>\n","answer_id":37399,"question_id":37250,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/37250/are-multi-chain-proteins-synthesized-as-one-biological-unit","last_activity_date":1441059553,"creation_date":1440679300,"answer_count":2,"title":"Are multi-chain proteins synthesized as one biological unit?","body":"<p>Are multi-chain proteins (especially homo/hetero-dimers) synthesized together as one overall unit or are they separate monomers which bind together at some point after synthesis, and are there any relevant factors to know about this process?<\/p>\n","question_id":37250,"tags":["proteins","protein-binding","protein-folding","protein-expression","protein-interaction"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":37313,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":59,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/67b48e241670a45e94066ff70d2c6cb8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":17606,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17606/bob","reputation":3,"display_name":"Bob"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb3c0063d438705f86396a8abc1b04a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12877,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12877/cmosychuk","reputation":4410,"display_name":"CMosychuk"},"score":0,"post_id":37388,"edited":false,"creation_date":1441046019,"comment_id":62814,"body":"I&#39;m looking at the life cycle for dengue virus, it looks like a positive-sense ssRNA virus. The viral genetic material doesn&#39;t integrate into the host genome. Someone correct me if I&#39;m wrong!"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/476e67c92121154e7910301e56cdfc4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":948,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/948/mattdmo","reputation":7591,"display_name":"MattDMo","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":37388,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb3c0063d438705f86396a8abc1b04a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12877,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12877/cmosychuk","reputation":4410,"display_name":"CMosychuk"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1441047253,"comment_id":62815,"body":"@Kendall you are correct. ss(+)RNA viral genomes behave like mRNA in the host, and are directly translated by ribosomes. The viral proteins thus produced then direct production of more genomes and the assembly of virus particles to infect more cells and other hosts. Viruses that integrate into the host&#39;s genome are called <i>retroviruses<\/i>."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/67b48e241670a45e94066ff70d2c6cb8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":17606,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17606/bob","reputation":3,"display_name":"Bob"},"score":0,"post_id":37388,"edited":false,"creation_date":1441047848,"comment_id":62817,"body":"Ah, thank you for the clarification. If you wouldn&#39;t mind posting that as an answer I could accept it."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb3c0063d438705f86396a8abc1b04a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12877,"link":"h