w.gravatar.com/avatar/12086f42e1380495f6b35592ce60b0e4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11652,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11652/stan-shunpike","reputation":819,"display_name":"Stan Shunpike","accept_rate":70},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/37392/what-is-the-decision-making-process-when-a-bird-builds-a-nest","last_activity_date":1441053149,"creation_date":1441048896,"answer_count":0,"title":"What is the decision making process when a bird builds a nest?","body":"<p>I have been watching <em>The Life of Birds<\/em> and I am rather startled by the ingenuity some birds show in building their nests. For instance, one species built a dummy nest on top with a secret entrance through the bottom. To predators, it looked like an empty nest when in reality the eggs were stored below. <\/p>\n\n<p>Now, if I wanted to build a house, I would make a plan. I would draw up blue prints, estimate how much material I would need, etc. But clearly birds do not do this.  They are not thinking in this way. Their problem solving clearly must involve some other mechanism, particularly since even species like insects know how to build nests.  <\/p>\n\n<p>What areas of the brain are involved in the complex behavior of nest building?  What is the decision making process when a bird builds a nest?<\/p>\n","question_id":37392,"tags":["brain"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":20,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1441053149},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/9ZslE.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1373,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1373/user1306322","reputation":578,"display_name":"user1306322","accept_rate":64},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4a170649404742ac048a2139560d8fdf?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9448,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9448/cognismantis","reputation":290,"display_name":"CognisMantis"},"score":1,"post_id":24189,"edited":false,"creation_date":1416518764,"comment_id":38602,"body":"stretching also occurs in animals that wake up and when yawning."},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user17608"},"score":0,"post_id":24189,"edited":false,"creation_date":1441049355,"comment_id":62850,"body":"Stretching is usually accommodated with a yawn in humans &amp; animals. This is because when we are tired &amp; sleepy, our breathing patterns slow down, letting half of the oxygen we normally breath in slow down to a minimum rate. When we wake, our body&#39;s suddenly needs to pull in a high amount of oxygen so we can function at full energy levels/ being alert. When we yawn, we pull high volumes of oxygen into the lungs which distribute it throughout our blood stream. When we stretch, this allows the oxygen breath in while yawning to flow throughout the body faster."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/v5upF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3624,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3624/fileunderwater","reputation":10502,"display_name":"fileunderwater"},"score":4,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1416528686,"creation_date":1416524689,"body":"<p>Humans and other animals have lots of innate behaviors that are not learned from observation, i.e. behaviors that are hard-wired into our nervous system, and this is one of them. <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primitive_reflexes#Sucking_reflex\" rel=\"nofollow\">Suckling reflexes<\/a> in mammals and the <a href=\"http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/article/003293.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">Moro reflex<\/a> is human babies (which we grow out of) are other simple examples.<\/p>\n\n<p>The stretching behaviours you are referring to are usually labelled <em>pandiculation<\/em> in humans (defined as involuntary stretching of the soft tissues), and yawning is often considered a special case of this. These kinds of behaviours are also normally related to transition periods between high-low activity in animals (<a href=\"http://www.medical-hypotheses.com/article/S0306-9877%2806%2900060-0/abstract\" rel=\"nofollow\" title=\"Walusinski. 2006. Yawning: Unsuspected avenue for a better understanding of arousal and interoception. Medical Hypotheses 67(1): 6\u201314\">Walusinskie, 2006<\/a>). In practice, stretching functions as a way to reverse the muscular atonia during REM sleep, and is in this sense a way to restore homeostatic functions (<a href=\"http://www.appliedanimalbehaviour.com/article/0168-1591%2889%2990117-2/abstract\" rel=\"nofollow\" title=\"Fraser. 1989. Pandiculation: the comparative phenomenon of systematic stretching. Applied Animal Behaviour Science 23(3): 263\u2013268\">Fraser, 1989<\/a>; <a href=\"http://www.medical-hypotheses.com/article/S0306-9877%2806%2900060-0/abstract\" rel=\"nofollow\" title=\"Walusinski. 2006. Yawning: Unsuspected avenue for a better understanding of arousal and interoception. Medical Hypotheses 67(1): 6\u201314\">Walusinskie, 2006<\/a>). <\/p>\n\n<p>A paper by <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20109487\" rel=\"nofollow\" title=\"Rial et al. 2010. Evolution of wakefulness, sleep and hibernation: from reptiles to mammals. Neurosci Biobehav Rev. 34(8):1144-60. doi: 10.1016/j.neubiorev.2010.01.008\">Rial et al (2010)<\/a> deals with the evolution of sleep and wakefulness in mammals from our reptile predecessors, and indicates that stretching behaviours might have originated/evolved from post-basking activities, more specifically risk-assessment behaviours, such as: <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>...risk assessment behaviour (RAB) and consists of the suspension of current behaviour, to be replaced by head dipping movements, eye scanning, rearing and\n  adopting stretch attending postures...<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>There is most likely much more to be said about this, and the paper cited above contains many references that can provide further clarification and evidence. A short comparative discussion of pandiculation is found in <a href=\"http://www.appliedanimalbehaviour.com/article/0168-1591%2889%2990117-2/abstract\" rel=\"nofollow\" title=\"Fraser. 1989. Pandiculation: the comparative phenomenon of systematic stretching. Applied Animal Behaviour Science 23(3): 263\u2013268\">Frasier (1989)<\/a>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":24196,"question_id":24189,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1416528686}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/24189/why-do-people-and-animals-stretch-out-their-bodies-and-what-is-causing-this-beha","last_activity_date":1441049355,"creation_date":1416502277,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why do people and animals stretch out their bodies and what is causing this behaviour?","body":"<p>I noticed that my cat which is only 6 months old has started stretching its body from time to time. Then I thought that this motion doesn't seem very natural from another cat's viewpoint, so my cat probably didn't try to imitate some other cat all of a sudden and learned it like that. This action must have been caused by something else then. Or at least that's what I think.<\/p>\n\n<p>Both animals and people stretch their muscles from time to time, but it doesn't seem to be caused by memory of others doing it. So how does this action originate in them?<\/p>\n","question_id":24189,"tags":["human-biology","zoology","ethology"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":24196,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":2523,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1416561355},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/79c437932eb8373e42f37e95d7357c59?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6340/darwin","reputation":274,"display_name":"Darwin"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id":16554,"edited":false,"creation_date":1397507321,"comment_id":22349,"body":"Does not answer your question but is related: <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sperm_competition\" rel=\"nofollow\">(inter-males) Sperm competition<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/210cc4a4b2f281aaffe0b26521fe1ab8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1590,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1590/rg255","reputation":11513,"display_name":"rg255","accept_rate":66},"score":0,"post_id":16554,"edited":false,"creation_date":1397509054,"comment_id":22351,"body":"<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/book/9780123725684\" rel=\"nofollow\">Sperm Biology: An evolutionary perspective<\/a> might help here - I&#39;ll take a look this week at work. There is also a group in my department looking at selection in the haploid/gametic phase so I&#39;ll chat to them."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/79c437932eb8373e42f37e95d7357c59?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6340/darwin","reputation":274,"display_name":"Darwin"},"score":0,"post_id":16558,"edited":false,"creation_date":1397546592,"comment_id":22368,"body":"Thanks for the answer. What&#39;s still confusing to me is the connection between a sperm not functioning properly and a potential human not functioning properly. For example, humans with mental retardation often have above average strength. Does that mean the sperm they 