\"Histopathologic features in esophagomyotomy specimens from patients with achalasia.\" Goldblum JR, Rice TW, Richter JE. Gastroenterology. 1996;111(3):648.<\/p>\n\n<p>EDIT:<\/p>\n\n<p>I answered the opposite, but the principles still apply. Here is a wonderful resource on this topic (\"Physiology of esophageal motility,\" <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/gimo/contents/pt1/full/gimo3.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.nature.com/gimo/contents/pt1/full/gimo3.html<\/a>. It includes a diagram showing the vagal neural pathway and the main neurotransmitters responsible for each action (relaxation and contraction).<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/XYuIK.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/XYuIK.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":37341,"question_id":37259,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1440989405}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/37259/what-neuro-motor-diseases-cause-the-lower-esophageal-sphincter-les-to-malfunct","last_activity_date":1440989405,"creation_date":1440693776,"answer_count":1,"title":"What neuro-motor diseases cause the lower esophageal sphincter (LES) to malfunction?","body":"<p><strong>Please note<\/strong>: This question is <em>neither<\/em> homework nor seeking medical advice. I'm simply asking for a factual, objective, biological explanation of the various neuro-motor diseases/illnesses that can act as the underlying cause to LES malfunction.<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>The primary function of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esophagus#Sphincters\" rel=\"nofollow\">lower esophageal sphincter (LES)<\/a> is to prevent stomach acid from backwashing into the esophagus. This sphincter is an involuntary muscle, and so, for it to malfunction (unable to fully or properly close), it must be the result of an underlying neuro-motor (autonomic) disease or condition.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>What such condition attacks this sphincter/valve, thereby causing it to malfunction and not operate properly? How exactly does this condition effect the sphincter biologically/neurologically?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<h3>Update<\/h3>\n\n<p>Looks like the Vagus Nerve (10th Cranial) innervates this sphincter, so I guess the question is: <em>What neuro-motor diseases attack the Vagus Nerve or cause it to malfunction?<\/em><\/p>\n","question_id":37259,"tags":["human-anatomy","muscles","neurology","gastroenterology","autonomic-nervous-system"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":37341,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":179,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1440978661},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/49e94b363348f897f337a5bce2beec20?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":68,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/68/marta-cz-c","reputation":1717,"display_name":"Marta Cz-C","accept_rate":50},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fdd630f72eef3790bfb4ef38d08c7f85?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":166,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/166/konrad-rudolph","reputation":3847,"display_name":"Konrad Rudolph"},"score":1,"post_id":935,"edited":false,"creation_date":1328564738,"comment_id":1104,"body":"Excellent question! A topic of active research and without clear consensus, as far as I remember from some talk."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/33af7b8879cdcdfdb5edb7b1f265fd9c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":430,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/430/richard-smith-unna","reputation":7703,"display_name":"Richard Smith-Unna","accept_rate":90},"score":0,"post_id":935,"edited":false,"creation_date":1328577852,"comment_id":1106,"body":"Great question, plenty to talk about here (give me a few days)."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4b21f13b2388dab1c90910e64b84e7a9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":452,"link":"http://biology