 this opinion.<\/p>\n\n<p>But, there are some methods to do so.\nLigating both ends with specific tags to amplify DNA fragments with the tag specific primer set. If you have different length of DNA fragments in original sample, PCR products could be biased. <\/p>\n","answer_id":37370,"question_id":37362,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/37362/is-it-possible-to-amplify-every-single-piece-of-dna-through-pcr","last_activity_date":1440983328,"creation_date":1440966426,"answer_count":2,"title":"Is it possible to amplify every single piece of DNA through PCR?","body":"<p>Is there a way to perform non-specific PCR amplification for the purpose of amplifying every piece of DNA present?<\/p>\n","question_id":37362,"tags":["genetics","dna","pcr"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":37370,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":42,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5545da6f0b045097e2954ec2fd5c007f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":17586,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17586/user17586","reputation":1,"display_name":"user17586"},"closed_date":1440999232,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/pVoco.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14587,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14587/the-nightman","reputation":1330,"display_name":"The Nightman","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":37349,"edited":false,"creation_date":1440946106,"comment_id":62730,"body":"I&#39;m a bit unclear what your question is. Are you asking what the general mutation rate is of genomic DNA, if anybody has looked at this, and if certain base pair changes are more common than others?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id"