ce in length of the autosomes is due to tandem duplications."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/37290/differing-flow-cytometry-genome-sizes-and-sexual-mating-implies-differing-chromo","last_activity_date":1440939429,"creation_date":1440759210,"answer_count":0,"title":"Differing Flow Cytometry Genome Sizes and Sexual Mating Implies Differing Chromosome Counts","body":"<p><strong>Do the fundamental principles of genetics strongly suggest the following is a derived conjecture?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p><strong><em>If 2 flowering plant species A and B have widely differing genome size (at a minimum a 50% difference) based on flow cytometry and normal successful sexual mating of A and B is indicated based on the flow cytometry measured genome sizes of the embryo and endosperm of the seeds produced by crossing A and B, then A and B differ in number of chromosomes to a degree indicative of ploidy level differences.<\/em><\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Corn, Cotton, and Rice are three genus where large genome size differences do not mean differences in chromosome counts. <\/p>\n\n<p>The Vireya in the genus Rhododendron are a group that have large genome size differences between species where multi-generational hybrids between such species appears to be possible at least in some cases. Documentation suggests that all Vireya have the same chromosome counts indicating diploids.<\/p>\n","question_id":37290,"tags":["chromosome","polyploidy","flow-cytometry"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":55,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1440939429},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/352620ba41c077bb6cf636b59bfd2fd3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17427,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17427/pi5","reputation":311,"display_name":"Pi5","accept_rate":25},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f524f51edb2e0e559de5f027217b2d47?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type